Dies irae, dies izm: These words of “startling suddenness'' with which the poet ushers in his theme are from the Prophet Sophonias: Dies irae, dies illa, dies tribulationis et angustiae, dies calamitatis et miseriae, dies tenebrarum et caliginis, dies nebulae et turbinis, dies tubae et clangoris (Soph. 1, 15-16). Solvet.- (cf. II Peter 3, 10). Teste David.- (cf. Pss. 10, 73 49, 3-6; and esp. 101, 26-28). Sibylla.- If any particular Sibyl is meant it is the Erythraean Sibyl, the author of the well-known acrostic on the name of Christ. However, “David and the Sibyl'’ here stand for Jew and Gentile, the witnesses respectively of inspiration and of mere natural religion. See the article on Sibyllina Ονασῑεε, in the cath. Encycl.
